Tokyo.address: Kabukicho, Shinjuku City, Tokyo 160-0021, Japan

reviews.text: A small district of 3-4 alleys full of incredibly tiny and crowded Japanese bars and izakayas. 5-6 seats at each bar. A special experience for the hard-core partygoers among us. Not for the faint of heart...

昔は大好きな街でしたが今はマナーの悪い外国人が多すぎて行けない街です。

This used to be my favorite part of Kabukicho — a small, charming alley full of unique bars and restaurants. Unfortunately, it’s been ruined by visitors who ignore basic manners and the local culture.

Many people now come here just to hang out in the street, drinking alcohol they bought at convenience stores, without entering any of the bars. They block the narrow pathways, take photos without permission or concern for others’ privacy, and smoke in shared spaces. These behaviors are not only disrespectful but disruptive to the local experience.

What many foreign visitors don’t understand is that charges like otoshi (a small starter dish) and seat fees are not scams — they are essential parts of how these small businesses survive. This isn’t a place for free, casual loitering. It’s a delicate ecosystem, and these customs exist to support the people who run it.

If you can’t respect the culture, the space, or the rules, then please don’t come. Your actions are making this place unwelcoming for those of us who truly love it. As a local Japanese person, it’s deeply disappointing, and I no longer feel comfortable visiting this area.

reviews.text:
Shinjuku Kabuki Yokocho at night is proof that Tokyo is a vibrant and atmospheric city, with its streets packed with locals and tourists. It will definitely be an unforgettable experience and worth a visit!
There is something for everyone, and Kabukicho has different entertainment options, bars, clubs, restaurants and more.

Shinjuku's nightlife is a dazzling spectacle of neon lights and bustling energy. The streets pulse with a vibrant mix of locals and tourists, exploring countless bars, clubs, and restaurants. From intimate jazz bars to lively karaoke spots and towering skyscrapers offering panoramic city views, there's something for everyone. Golden Gai's narrow alleys reveal hidden gems, while Kabukicho teems with entertainment. The atmosphere is electric, a sensory overload of sounds, sights, and smells. Shinjuku at night is an unforgettable experience, a testament to Tokyo's dynamic and exciting urban culture.
The street is really like Shinjuku itself.

Very good view
Hypnotizing place. The visit is totally worth it just to watch the busy streets and railways

A must see at night - One of the famous vantage points in Tokyo to capture Japanese life in full swing. Here you can witness trains arriving and departing Shinjuku, the worlds busiest train station, pedestrians crossing, Cars and buses all underneath the vibrant Tokyo skyline. Was a few other people also taking photos and videos but were all out of each others way so should have no issues making timelapses or getting that perfect shot!
You should definitely take photos there.
It was rainy and windy and the road there was cold, but it was so pretty that I had no regrets.
